rComments: UofT was narrow in its minority-centric course offerings. Despite being an introvert in RLG201Y, Doc stepped up with his expertise in comparative religion and psychology of religion, offering to supervise a directed reading elective in comparative religious symbolism and ritual spaces. He pushed me to excel and am better for having known him!

Not a Beads & Feathers course for those with stereotypical prejudices. Rather, Doc provided an in-depth course in comparative Aboriginal Spiritual practices. He was very accommodating to his students regardless of race. Its a shame UofT cancelled the course among other minority-centric religion courses. Kept attending even after passing with an A!

Doc was an interesting prof, he was very knowledgeable and at times helpful, other times he was hard to approach and very arrogant towards students, thus making it hard to approach him. The material is interesting although at times is extremely thick and hard to get into to. He does tend to favor the students who suck up to him however.
Least favorite prof in the 3 Religious Studies courses I took at U of T. Dropped the class and never looked back. (Until now.)

Not for the faint at heart; Prof is extrem. knowledgeable and presents views & facts that have been kept from society; welcomes/encourages student comments/ideas, both during class and out; is the most helpful, supportive & caring Prof I've met; very humble and gentle in nature; He is also comical. Course material is extrem. facinating. A++++
A nasty, small-minded man abusing a position of minor authority.
